title: Gamma-ray production by proton and alpha-particle induced reactions on C-12, O-16, Mg and Fe.

x4freetext: Gamma-ray production by proton and alpha-particle
induced reactions on C-12, O-16, Mg and Fe.

x4codes.hlp: Centre Sci. Nucl. et Sci. Matiere (CSNSM), Orsay, France

x4freetext: Self-supporting targets foils of C, Mg-24 and Fe and
of MgO mounted on a thin Al foils. The different
targets were fixed onto brass frames and arranged on  a
multiple target holder, which could be shifted
vertically to place the different materials into the
beam. Two carbon foils were 0.54 and 0.76-mg/cm**2
thickness, a MgO foil was approximately 2-mg/cm**2 for
measurements of the 4.438 MeV line shape. For gamma-ray
production on Mg-24 and Fe, an isotopically pure Mg-24
thick foil of natural iron, respectively were used.
In additional to runs with the different targets which
lasted typically 30 min, runs for most beam energies
with an empty frame were used to determine part of the
The induced gamma rays were detected by a
set of five high efficiency HP-Ge detectors with
bismuth germinate(BGO) scintillator shields for active
Compton suppression from the Eurogam phase I setup.

x4codes.hlp: Centre Sci. Nucl. et Sci. Matiere (CSNSM), Orsay, France

x4freetext: The gamma-ray fluxes at the different detector angles
were obtained with the dead-time-corrected line
Two procedures were used-simple integration of
line counts with subtraction of a background estimated
from count levels below and above the peak and a
standard fitting procedure with parametrized response
of Ge detectors to (practically) monoenergetic gamma-
Both procedures were usually employed for narrow lines,
giving an estimate of the uncertainty due to the
background subtraction which was added quadratically
correspond to half the energy loss in the target.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: .Th quoted uncertainties on the cross section
are taken from the results of fits.They contain thereby
for dead-time correction, background subtraction and
detector efficiencies. To these should be added an
overall uncertainty in the cross-section normalization,
which is estimated to be less than 10% for data taken
with the carbon targets and 15% with the MgO target.
It includes uncertainties in the target thickness,
which was approx. 7% for the two carbon targets and
approx. 15% for the MgO target, beam charge
The overall uncertainties in the cross-section
normalization with iron target and the isotopically
enriched Mg-24 target were less than 5% for the iron
target and less than 10% for the Mg-24 target.
Uncertainties in the target thickness were less than 5%
for the iron target and less than 7% for the Mg-24
